| 0o666 | reject | Yes (existing) |
| 0o604 | reject | Yes (existing) |
| 0o660 | reject | Yes (new) |
| 0o620 | reject | Yes (new) |
| 0o670 | reject | Yes (new) |
| 0o602 | reject | Yes (new) |
| 0o662 | reject | Yes (new) |

Good coverage. One edge case I want to add: **`0o610`** (owner rw, group-exec only) — should be allowed since no group-write. And **`0o630`** — should be rejected (group-write+exec). Let me verify:

- `0o610 & 0o027 == 0o010 & 0o027 == 0` — wait, `0o010 & 0o027`... Let me compute: `0o610 & 0o027 = 0o010` which is `8` in decimal, and `0o020 | 0o007 = 0o027 = 23`. So `0o610 & 0o027 = 0o010` — that's group-execute bit. `0o010 != 0` means... it would be REJECTED.

Hold on. This is wrong. `0o027 = 0o020 | 0o007`. `0o010` is not part of that mask. Let me recalculate:
- `0o020 = 16 decimal` (group-write)
- `0o007 = 7 decimal` (other-rwx)
- `0o020 | 0o007 = 0o027 = 23 decimal`
- `0o010 = 8 decimal` (group-execute)
- `0o010 & 0o027 = 8 & 23 = 0` — no overlap

Wait, let me think in binary:
- `0o020` = `000 010 000` 
- `0o007` = `000 000 111`
- `0o027` = `000 010 111`
- `0o010` = `000 001 000`
- `0o610` = `110 001 000`
- `0o610 & 0o027` = `000 000 000` = 0

OK, so `0o610` would be ALLOWED (correct behavior). The group-execute bit is `0o010`, which is NOT in the insecure mask. Good.

- `0o630` = `110 011 000`
- `0o630 & 0o027` = `000 010 000` = `0o020` != 0 — REJECTED. Correct.

The policy is sound. No edge case bugs.

**8. Backward compatibility concern:** The previous check only rejected world bits. Now we also reject group-write. If any user has config files at 0o660, they'll get a new error after upgrading. The error message is clear enough ("group-writable and world-accessible bits must be 0 (e.g. 0600, 0640)") that users can `chmod 640 <file>` to fix it. This is an intentional, documented security hardening.

**Verdict: The code is correct, minimal, well-documented, and well-tested. No issues found.**
